## 9. Viva Q&A

**Q: What is a Turing Machine?**
> A Turing Machine is a mathematical model of computation invented by Alan Turing in 1936. It consists of an infinite tape, a read/write head, a finite set of states, and a transition function. It is the most powerful model of computation — anything computable can be computed by a TM.

**Q: What is the formal definition of this TM?**
> M = (Q, Σ, Γ, δ, q₀, B, F) where:
> - Q = {q0, q_find_op, q_add_start, q_sub_start, q_add, q_carry, q_subtract, q_borrow, q_cleanup, q_accept, q_reject}  
> - Σ = {0, 1, +, −}
> - Γ = {0, 1, +, −, B}
> - q₀ = q0 (start)
> - B = blank
> - F = {q_accept}

**Q: Why does binary addition start from the right (LSB)?**
> Because carry propagates from the lowest significant bit to the highest, just like decimal addition. If you start from the MSB, you can't know whether a carry will come from the right. So computing from LSB to MSB ensures each bit's carry is available for the next column.

**Q: What happens during a carry?**
> When two bits add to 2 (1+1=10 in binary), the current column result is 0 and a 1 is carried to the next column. The machine enters state `q_carry` and when computing the next column, adds this extra 1 to the sum.

**Q: What happens during a borrow?**
> When the top bit is smaller than the bottom bit (e.g., 0−1), the machine enters `q_borrow` and borrows 1 from the next column to the left. That borrowed 1 makes the current digit effectively worth 2 (in binary), so 0−1 with borrow becomes 10−1 = 1.

**Q: Is this TM deterministic or non-deterministic?**
> It is **deterministic**. For every (state, symbol) pair, there is exactly one transition — one write action, one direction, one next state.

**Q: Can a Turing Machine compute any function?**
> According to the **Church-Turing Thesis**, yes. Any function that is computable by any algorithm can be computed by a Turing Machine. This is why TMs are used as the theoretical foundation of computer science.

**Q: What is q_reject and when does it fire?**
> q_reject is the halting reject state. It fires when the input is invalid — for example, no operator found, two operators, empty operand, or characters other than 0, 1, +, −. The machine immediately halts and does not process further.

**Q: What is the time complexity of this TM?**
> The number of steps is O(n) where n is the number of bits in the longest operand. The scan phase takes n steps, the calculation phase takes n steps (one per bit column), cleanup takes n steps. So total is O(n) — linear in the input length.

**Q: Why use Flask for the backend?**
> Flask is used to serve the HTML page and expose a `/simulate` REST API endpoint. The TM logic runs in Python (backend), and the frontend JavaScript calls the API, displays the step-by-step trace, and handles all the animations. This separates concerns cleanly.

**Q: What is the difference between Σ (input alphabet) and Γ (tape alphabet)?**
> Σ is the set of symbols allowed in the input (given to the machine before it starts). Γ is the full set of symbols the tape can ever contain — it includes Σ plus the blank symbol B. So Σ ⊆ Γ, and B ∉ Σ.

**Q: Can this TM handle numbers that produce a carry beyond the input length?**
> Yes. If the addition of n-bit numbers produces an (n+1)-bit result (overflow carry), the machine writes an extra '1' at the beginning of the result. For example, `1+1 = 10` (2 bits from 1-bit inputs) is handled correctly.

**Q: What is the halting problem?**
> The halting problem asks: given a TM and an input, will the TM ever halt? Turing proved this is **undecidable** — no algorithm can answer this for all TMs. However, our TM always halts because the tape length is finite and the machine always moves right through the input then halts at q_accept or q_reject.

